          "number": 1,
          "title": "Bringing nature back: the science and controversy of rewilding",
          "bodyParagraphs": [
            "In the latter decades of the twentieth century, conservation efforts tended to focus on protecting what remained of the natural world: maintaining reserves, controlling invasive species and preventing further habitat loss. More recently, a more ambitious approach has begun to take hold. Rewilding, broadly defined as the large-scale restoration of ecosystems by reintroducing species and reducing human management, has attracted growing interest among scientists, policymakers and the public. Its advocates argue that passive conservation is no longer enough — that genuinely recovering nature requires actively putting back what has been lost.",
            "The scientific foundation of rewilding rests on the concept of trophic cascades: the idea that apex predators, by controlling the populations of the animals they hunt, can reshape entire ecosystems in ways that benefit biodiversity and even influence landscape and climate. The most widely cited example is the reintroduction of wolves to Yellowstone National Park in the United States in 1995. Research subsequently found that wolf predation caused elk to avoid grazing in certain areas, allowing vegetation to recover, riverbanks to stabilise and a range of other species to return. Although some ecologists have disputed the scale of these effects, the Yellowstone case remains a central reference point for rewilding proponents.",
            "In Europe, the organisation Rewilding Europe has facilitated the return of bison, wild horses and other large herbivores to areas of Portugal, Romania, Spain and Sweden. In the Cairngorms in Scotland, the conservation charity Trees for Life is working to restore the ancient Caledonian forest through a combination of deer management and native tree planting. These projects represent a significant shift in how European societies think about land and its proper use.",
            "The reintroduction of apex predators remains the most contentious aspect of rewilding. In the UK, proposals to bring back lynx to parts of northern England and Scotland have been met with strong opposition from farming communities, who fear for the safety of livestock. In Germany, wolves that have returned to the country naturally have caused significant conflict with sheep farmers. Dr Mark Fisher of the University of Leeds, who has written extensively on rewilding in densely populated European landscapes, acknowledges the difficulty: 'Rewilding works well in sparsely inhabited areas where there is space for large predators to operate. In a country like the UK, the socio-political obstacles are enormous.'",
            "Supporters of rewilding point to a growing body of evidence demonstrating its ecological value. Studies of rewilded sites in the Netherlands and Denmark have recorded substantial increases in insect diversity within just a few years of reducing intensive land management. Research published in the journal Nature has suggested that allowing forests to recover on as little as 15% of the world's most degraded land could prevent up to 60% of projected species extinctions and absorb a significant fraction of the carbon released since industrialisation began.",
            "The land question is, however, a significant barrier. Most of the world's productive land is in agricultural use, and the prospect of taking large areas out of production to allow ecosystem recovery raises serious concerns about food security. Anna Fitzpatrick, a rural policy researcher at University College Dublin, argues that the trade-off between rewilding ambitions and food production needs to be handled with care: 'We cannot simply export our food needs to other parts of the world and call it an environmental victory. The land-use implications of large-scale rewilding have to be addressed honestly.'",
            "Despite these tensions, interest in rewilding is spreading beyond traditional conservation circles. Several large landowners in the UK and continental Europe have begun transitioning their estates away from intensive farming towards rewilding projects. Some have found that ecotourism, carbon credits and government conservation payments can, over time, generate revenue comparable to agricultural income. Whether these economic models can scale to produce the landscape-level change that rewilding requires, however, is still far from clear."
          ],
          "questionSectionText": "Questions 1–4\nWhich section contains the following information?\nWrite the correct letter, A–G, in boxes 1–4 on your answer sheet.\n\n1 a reference to evidence that rewilding can benefit both biodiversity and the global climate\n2 an acknowledgement that rewilding is more easily achieved in regions with low human populations\n3 a description of specific rewilding work that is taking place in Scotland\n4 a warning that transferring food production to other countries does not solve the land-use problem\n\nQuestions 5–8\nComplete the summary below.\nChoose ONE WORD ONLY from the passage for each answer.\n\nWolves and the Yellowstone effect\n\nThe reintroduction of wolves to Yellowstone in 1995 is the most frequently cited example of a 5 ......... cascade. When wolves hunted elk, the elk changed their 6 ......... habits, which allowed plants to grow back in previously bare areas. This in turn helped 7 ......... along rivers to become more stable and encouraged the return of other species. However, some scientists have 8 ......... the extent of these changes.\n\nQuestions 9–13\nLook at the following statements and the list of people below.\nMatch each statement with the correct person, A–D.\n\nList of people\nA  Dr Mark Fisher\nB  Anna Fitzpatrick\nC  Rewilding Europe\nD  researchers cited in paragraph E\n\n9 Rewilding projects in Europe have successfully brought back a range of large animal species.\n10 The land taken out of production for rewilding must not simply shift its food burden to other countries.\n11 Dense human settlement creates challenges for rewilding that go beyond the purely scientific.\n12 Recovering degraded land could play a significant role in preventing species loss and reducing carbon in the atmosphere.\n13 The economic and political barriers to rewilding in heavily populated European countries are very great.",
