          "number": 1,
          "title": "The fungal frontier: mycelium as a sustainable material",
          "bodyParagraphs": [
            "The global packaging industry generates hundreds of millions of tonnes of polystyrene and single-use plastic foam each year. These materials are effective insulators and shock absorbers, but they are derived from petroleum, are almost impossible to recycle in practice, and persist in the environment for centuries. As pressure grows on manufacturers to reduce their reliance on fossil-fuel-based materials, researchers and entrepreneurs have turned to an unexpected source: fungi. The root-like network of fibres that forms the body of a fungus, known as mycelium, can be grown into moulds to produce lightweight, strong and fully biodegradable material with properties strikingly similar to polystyrene foam.",
            "Mycelium grows naturally by threading its fibres through organic matter such as agricultural waste, binding the particles together as it expands. By controlling the growing conditions — temperature, humidity and the composition of the substrate — manufacturers can influence the density, rigidity and texture of the final material. Once the desired shape has been achieved, the growing process is halted by applying heat, which kills the mycelium and prevents further growth. The result is a rigid, dry material that can be composted at the end of its useful life and returns completely to the soil within weeks.",
            "The commercial potential of mycelium materials was first demonstrated by the American company Ecovative Design, founded in New York State in 2007. Ecovative developed a process for growing mycelium around agricultural residues such as corn husks and hemp hurds to produce packaging materials that function as drop-in replacements for polystyrene. The Swedish furniture company IKEA announced in 2021 that it was exploring the use of mycelium packaging for some of its products, reflecting the growing interest of major manufacturers in bio-based alternatives to conventional foam.",
            "Beyond packaging, researchers are investigating the structural properties of mycelium for use in construction. Teams at institutions including Delft University of Technology in the Netherlands and the BioMASON laboratory in North Carolina have produced mycelium-based bricks and panels that are fire-resistant, water-repellent and comparable in compressive strength to conventional insulation materials. A temporary pavilion constructed from mycelium bricks was exhibited at the Museum of Modern Art in New York, demonstrating the material's architectural potential.",
            "Scaling mycelium production to industrial levels, however, presents significant engineering challenges. Growing biological material requires careful environmental control, and maintaining consistent product quality across large batches has proved difficult. Dr Franziska Noll of the Fraunhofer Institute for Interfacial Engineering in Stuttgart, who has studied the commercialisation of bio-based materials, notes that 'the biological variability of living organisms is the central challenge. Unlike a chemical reaction that produces the same output every time, a living system responds to tiny fluctuations in its environment, and that variability is very hard to eliminate at scale.'",
            "Questions have also been raised about whether mycelium materials are suitable for structural applications in the built environment. Current building regulations in most countries require materials to meet strict and well-established performance standards that have not yet been comprehensively tested for mycelium-based products. Professor Hassan Bilal of Sheffield Hallam University, who advises the UK construction industry on emerging materials, cautions that 'enthusiasm for novel bio-based materials should not run ahead of the evidence. We need long-term data on how these materials perform under real-world conditions before they can be approved for general construction use.'",
            "The mycelium materials sector nevertheless continues to grow. Ecovative has expanded into producing mycelium-based leather alternatives and meat substitutes, demonstrating the versatility of the platform beyond packaging. Investment in the sector has increased substantially, driven partly by tightening regulations on single-use plastics in the European Union and the United Kingdom. If production challenges can be resolved and regulatory frameworks developed, mycelium materials could displace polystyrene across a wide range of applications — offering a fully compostable alternative grown not from oil, but from agricultural waste."
          ],
